# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: svelte-docs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] Markup inside a Svelte component can be thought of as HTML++.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] A lowercase tag, like `<div>`, denotes a regular HTML element.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] A capitalised tag or a tag that uses dot notation, such as `<Widget>` or `<my.stuff>`, indicates a *component*.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] By default, attributes work exactly like their HTML counterparts.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] Attribute values can contain JavaScript expressions.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] Or they can *be* JavaScript expressions.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] Boolean attributes are included on the element if their value is truthy and excluded if it's falsy.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] All other attributes are included unless their value is nullish (`null` or `undefined`).
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] When the attribute name and value match (`name={name}`), they can be replaced with `{name}`.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] By convention, values passed to components are referred to as *properties* or *props* rather than *attributes*, which are a feature of the DOM.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] As with elements, `name={name}` can be replaced with the `{name}` shorthand.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] An element or component can have multiple spread attributes, interspersed with regular ones.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] Listening to DOM events is possible by adding attributes to the element that start with `on`.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] `onclick` listens to the `click` event, `onClick` listens to the `Click` event, which is different.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] This ensures you can listen to custom events that have uppercase characters in them.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] Timing-wise, event attributes always fire after events from bindings (e.g.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] `oninput` always fires after an update to `bind:value`).
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] Under the hood, some event handlers are attached directly with `addEventListener`, while others are *delegated*.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] When using `ontouchstart` and `ontouchmove` event attributes, the handlers are passive for better performance.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] This greatly improves responsiveness by allowing the browser to scroll the document immediately, rather than waiting to see if the event handler calls `event.preventDefault()`.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] In the very rare cases that you need to prevent these event defaults, you should use `on` instead (for example inside an action).
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] To reduce memory footprint and increase performance, Svelte uses a technique called event delegation.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] This means that for certain events — see the list below — a single event listener at the application root takes responsibility for running any handlers on the event's path.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] A JavaScript expression can be included as text by surrounding it with curly braces.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] Expressions that are `null` or `undefined` will be omitted; all others are coerced to strings.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] Curly braces can be included in a Svelte template by using their HTML entity strings: `&lbrace;`, `&lcub;`, or `&#123;` for `{` and `&rbrace;`, `&rcub;`, or `&#125;` for `}`.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] If you're using a regular expression (`RegExp`) literal notation, you'll need to wrap it in parentheses.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] The expression will be stringified and escaped to prevent code injections.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] If you want to render HTML, use the `{@html}` tag instead.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] You can use HTML comments inside components.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] Comments beginning with `svelte-ignore` disable warnings for the next block of markup.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] Usually, these are accessibility warnings; make sure that you're disabling them for a good reason.
[src:svelte-docs/basic-markup] You can add a special comment starting with `@component` that will show up when hovering over the component name in other files.
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-files] Components are the building blocks of Svelte applications.
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-files] They are written into `.svelte` files, using a superset of HTML.
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-files] All three sections — script, styles and markup — are optional.
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-files] A `<script>` block contains JavaScript (or TypeScript, when adding the `lang="ts"` attribute) that runs when a component instance is created.
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-files] Variables declared (or imported) at the top level can be referenced in the component's markup.
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-files] In addition to normal JavaScript, you can use *runes* to declare component props and add reactivity to your component.
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-files] A `<script>` tag with a `module` attribute runs once when the module first evaluates, rather than for each component instance.
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-files] Variables declared in this block can be referenced elsewhere in the component, but not vice versa.
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-files] You can `export` bindings from this block, and they will become exports of the compiled module.
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-files] You cannot `export default`, since the default export is the component itself.
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-files] CSS inside a `<style>` block will be scoped to that component.
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-files] For more information, head to the section on styling.
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-overview] Svelte is a framework for building user interfaces on the web.
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-overview] It uses a compiler to turn declarative components written in HTML, CSS and JavaScript...
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-overview] ...into lean, tightly optimized JavaScript.
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-overview] You can use it to build anything on the web, from standalone components to ambitious full stack apps (using Svelte's companion application framework, SvelteKit) and everything in between.
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-overview] These pages serve as reference documentation.
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-overview] If you're new to Svelte, we recommend starting with the interactive tutorial and coming back here when you have questions.
[src:svelte-docs/svelte-overview] You can also try Svelte online in the playground or, if you need a more fully-featured environment, on StackBlitz.
